    "summary": "Piezanet needed more than a visual refresh: the brand, catalog structure, and interface logic all felt disconnected. I rebuilt the identity, defined the token and component foundations, and translated them into a responsive commerce experience that improves product discovery, brand recognition, and developer handoff.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "label": "OVERVIEW",
        "heading": "",
        "body": "Piezanet needed more than a visual refresh: the brand, catalog structure, and interface logic all felt disconnected. I rebuilt the identity, defined the token and component foundations, and translated them into a responsive commerce experience that improves product discovery, brand recognition, and developer handoff."
      },
      {
        "label": "OOUX & INFORMATION ARCHITECTURE",
        "heading": "",
        "body": "I used OOUX to define the primary objects, relationships, and browsing paths before touching visual style. That object model shaped the information architecture, so product categories, support content, and conversion flows could all follow the same logic."
      },
      {
        "label": "COMMERCE DIRECTION",
        "heading": "",
        "body": "That structural work led to a shop experience where the products lead, the content supports decision-making, and the route from browsing to checkout feels more intentional and easier to trust."
      },
      {
        "label": "LOGO, TYPE & TOKENS",
        "heading": "",
        "body": "The system starts with foundations: logo, color, typography, semantic tokens, spacing, and naming conventions that keep the interface coherent before screens are even assembled."
      },
      {
        "label": "TYPOGRAPHY & SPACING",
        "heading": "",
        "body": "I documented how type scales across desktop and mobile, how spacing behaves in layout, and which rules stay fixed versus flexible across the system."
      },
      {
        "label": "COMMERCE PATTERNS",
        "heading": "",
        "body": "I built reusable commerce patterns for the shop experience, including product cards, category cards, filters, pagination, inputs, icons, and shared layout elements with consistent states and spacing logic."
      },
      {
        "label": "SCALABLE UI",
        "heading": "",
        "body": "This made the interface easier to extend and easier to hand over, because recurring UI was defined as a system rather than redesigned screen by screen."
      },
      {
        "label": "DEVELOPER DELIVERY",
        "heading": "",
        "body": "The file was structured so a developer could understand the system quickly: foundations, components, screens, and flow were grouped clearly, with annotations for usage, states, and edge cases."
      },
      {
        "label": "FILE STRUCTURE",
        "heading": "",
        "body": "It documents not just final screens, but how the design should be read, how variants are organised, and where implementation details need attention."
      },
      {
        "label": "",
        "heading": "",
        "body": "A brand-led commerce system with documented foundations, reusable UI, and developer-ready handoff."
      }
    ],
